{
"analysis": "The previous step computed global P95 thresholds for all component-KPI series and compared each point in the incident window (2021-03-09 16:30→17:00+08) against those thresholds. The compact anomaly table shows many groups with every point flagged as anomalous in the window, but a large portion of those have global_p95 == 0, producing infinite severity ratios. These zero-baseline KPIs (TCP state counters, session counters, etc.) are noisy for ratio-based severity and should be de-emphasized. To find plausible root-cause candidates we must focus on component-KPIs with meaningful non-zero baselines (global_p95 > 0) and significant deviations (high severity_ratio) and/or sustained consecutive anomalies. From the earlier aggregates, promising non-zero baseline KPIs include IG01 JVM memory series and Tomcat04 request/processing time KPIs, but we need a concise ranked anomaly summary that excludes zero-baseline series to confirm which components show the strongest, sustained breaches during the incident window.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using metric.csv and the precomputed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) (do NOT recompute P95 using only the window), filter to rows in the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08. Consider only component-KPIs whose global_p95 > 0. For each such (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count (points with value >= global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95, and severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95. Return a compact table (max 20 rows) sorted by severity_ratio descending then anomaly_point_count descending, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio. Limit output to top 20 rows." 
}

{
"analysis": "The previous metric analysis identified multiple isolated, high-severity single-point spikes within the incident window (2021-03-09 16:30→17:00+08). Notable candidates: MG02 TCP-FIN-WAIT at 16:56, Mysql01 'Com Insert' at 16:30, Mysql02 long-running SQL metrics at 16:43, and several node/local-disk and TCP state spikes across IG01/IG02/Apache/Tomcat. Most metric anomalies are single-sample spikes rather than sustained faults. Since several database-related metrics (Mysql01/Mysql02) show strong spikes (severity_ratio ≈ 19) clustered around 16:30–16:43, and because trace analysis is required to determine which service is the downstream faulty component when multiple components show anomalies, the next step is to analyze trace features (durations and row_counts) within the same incident window. This will help identify which service/container shows elevated latencies or row counts coincident with the metric spikes and thus likely the root-cause component.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using trace.csv, first compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) over the full available series (do NOT restrict to the incident window). Then filter trace.csv to rows within 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within that window, identify points where value >= global_P95. Produce a compact summary (max 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95 (report inf if global_p95==0). Sort by severity_ratio descending then anomaly_point_count descending and return the top 20 rows." 
}

{
"analysis": "We computed global P95 thresholds for metrics and traces, filtered the incident window (2021-03-09 16:30→17:00+08), and produced compact anomaly summaries. Metric analysis found several high-severity single-point spikes (notably Mysql01 at 16:30 and Mysql02 long-running SQL metrics at 16:43 with severity_ratio ≈ 19). Trace analysis found transient latency/row_count increases across MG01/MG02/dockerA*/dockerB* and IG→Tomcat paths; the strongest single trace deviation is MG01 trace.from_root.duration_mean at 16:53 (+≈70% vs P95). Most anomalies are isolated 1–2 point spikes rather than sustained faults. According to the workflow, we must now localize faults by correlating specific anomaly timestamps between metrics and traces and then inspect logs for supporting evidence. The most promising candidates to inspect next are: Mysql01, Mysql02 (large metric spikes at ~16:30 and ~16:43), and MG01/MG02/dockerA*/dockerB* (trace latency spikes around ~16:32–16:53). To avoid broad outputs, we should extract the actual trace anomaly rows (timestamp and value) within the incident window for these candidate components so we can map exact timestamps and see whether anomalies cluster into a fault period.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) over the full trace.csv series (do NOT restrict by the incident window for threshold). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and identify rows where value >= that global_P95. Restrict the search to these components only: MG01, MG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, IG01, dockerA1, dockerA2, dockerB1, dockerB2. Return a compact table (limit 50 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, timestamp, value. Also return a small aggregate table (one row per cmdb_id) showing for each of the listed components: total_anomaly_rows_in_window and earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Keep outputs bounded (max 50 detail rows, and one summary row per component)." 
}

{
"analysis": "We compared metrics and traces across the incident window and found that most metric anomalies are isolated single-point spikes (not sustained faults)—notably Mysql01/Mysql02 spikes at ~16:30–16:43. In contrast, trace anomalies are widespread and sustained for MG01 and MG02 (MG02: 84 anomalous trace rows, MG01: 81 rows across the window), and many dockerA/dockerB nodes also show repeated trace anomalies. Logs and error_logs contain no useful error entries (error_logs empty; log.error_count P95 = 0 for many services), so logs haven't yet confirmed an application error. According to the diagnosis workflow, we should now treat MG01/MG02 as primary fault candidates and identify true 'fault' intervals (consecutive anomalous minutes) in their trace series rather than isolated spikes. This will tell us the first occurrence time of sustained anomalies (candidate root-cause occurrence) and help decide if MG01 or MG02 (or downstream services in traces) is the root cause. Mysql spikes remain important but are likely transient; they had no corresponding trace anomalies in the window.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "For trace.csv, compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series (do NOT restrict to the window). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and restrict to components MG01 and MG02 only. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name), identify consecutive sequences of timestamps where value >= global_p95 (consecutive by minute). For each detected consecutive sequence (a 'fault interval') report: cmdb_id, trace_name, interval_start_timestamp, interval_end_timestamp, length_in_minutes (number of points), max_value_in_interval, global_p95, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_interval - global_p95)/global_p95 (use inf if global_p95==0). Return two tables: 1) a fault-interval table limited to top 20 intervals sorted by length_in_minutes desc then severity_ratio desc; 2) a per-component summary with cmdb_id, total_fault_intervals_detected, longest_interval_length, earliest_interval_start. Keep outputs compact and bounded." }

{
"analysis": "We detected many short fault-intervals (mostly 2-minute bursts) across MG01 and MG02 traces during 2021-03-09 16:30→17:00+08. MG02 has slightly more intervals (77) than MG01 (63). The trace anomalies are widespread (row_count and duration spikes) and recur across dockerA/dockerB and Tomcat calls, suggesting brief but pervasive latency/queuing events in the MG layer. Metric anomalies earlier pointed to isolated spikes in Mysql nodes and some disk/network spikes on IG/MG/Apache, but MySQL had no matching trace anomalies. To localize the root cause we must inspect MG01 and MG02 host/resource metrics in the incident window to identify which resource (CPU, memory, disk I/O, network states) exhibits sustained/consecutive anomalies that could explain the trace bursts.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) over the full available series (do NOT restrict by time). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and restrict to components MG01 and MG02. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) within that window, identify rows where value >= global_p95. Produce a compact summary table (max 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95 (report inf if global_p95==0). Sort by severity_ratio desc then anomaly_point_count desc and return the table." 
}

{
"analysis": "We followed the prescribed workflow: calculated global P95s, performed metric-level anomaly detection, then trace analysis and fault-interval detection. Results so far show: (1) many isolated high-severity single-point metric spikes on DB nodes (Mysql01/Mysql02) around ~16:30–16:43; (2) pervasive short (mostly 2-minute) trace fault-intervals across MG01 and MG02 and many docker nodes throughout 16:30→17:00+08, with MG02 having slightly more intervals than MG01; (3) logs/error_logs contain no clear error evidence (error_logs empty, log.error_count P95 = 0 for many services). Many metric anomalies for MG01/MG02 are flagged only because their global P95 == 0 (zero baseline), which makes ratio-based severity meaningless. Given MG-level trace intervals are numerous and recurring, the next logical step is to check MG01/MG02 resource KPIs (CPU, memory, disk I/O, network) but focusing only on KPIs with a meaningful non-zero global baseline so we can find sustained metric faults (consecutive breaches) that could explain the trace bursts. If we find a sustained metric fault on MG01 or MG02 (e.g., high CPU, high disk I/O, or high network error/queue with non-zero baseline) with an earliest occurrence timestamp that matches the trace fault intervals, that will identify the root-cause component, occurrence time, and resource reason. Otherwise, the issue may be transient network blips or distributed short-lived queuing across MG layer.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric.csv series (do NOT filter by window for thresholds). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and restrict to components MG01 and MG02. From those, keep only KPIs whose global_p95 > 0. For each remaining (cmdb_id,kpi_name) detect consecutive sequences (by minute) where value >= global_p95. For every detected consecutive sequence (a metric 'fault interval') report: cmdb_id, kpi_name, interval_start_timestamp, interval_end_timestamp, length_in_minutes, max_value_in_interval, global_p95, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_interval - global_p95)/global_p95. Return two bounded outputs: 1) a fault-interval table limited to the top 20 intervals sorted by length_in_minutes desc then severity_ratio desc; 2) a per-component summary with cmdb_id, total_fault_intervals_detected, longest_interval_length, earliest_interval_start. Keep outputs compact (max 20 rows in interval table)."
}

{
"analysis": "We have followed the prescribe workflow: computed global thresholds, detected metric anomalies (many single-point DB spikes), analyzed traces (widespread short trace fault-intervals concentrated on MG01/MG02 and many docker/Tomcat paths), and identified metric fault-intervals on MG01/MG02. Most metric flags on MG hosts are due to P95==0 (zero baseline) and therefore produce meaningless infinite severity ratios; only a few MG JVM memory KPIs show modest positive severity. Trace anomalies show the largest relative deviation was MG01 trace.from_root.duration_mean (~+70% at 16:53) and many row_count spikes on MG around 16:56–16:59. MySQL metric spikes (≈16:30–16:43) do not align with trace anomalies and had no matching trace anomalies. To decide the single root cause among multiple candidates we must use traces to locate the most downstream faulty service in the call chains. The next step is to inspect trace anomalies for Tomcat services (Tomcat01–Tomcat04) within the incident window to see whether any downstream Tomcat shows sustained/earlier or more severe anomalies that would make it the root cause of the MG trace bursts.",
