"instruction": "Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) over the full trace.csv series (do NOT restrict to the incident window for thresholds). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and restrict to traces related to Tomcat services (cmdb_id in [Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04] and trace_name containing 'to_Tomcat' or 'from_Tomcat' or 'trace.self'). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in that set, count total points in window, count anomaly points where value >= global_p95, find earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95, and severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95 (report inf if global_p95==0). Return a compact table (max 20 rows) sorted by severity_ratio desc then anomaly_point_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio." }

{
"analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, calculated global P95s, and performed metric and trace anomaly analyses within the incident window (2021-03-09 16:30→17:00+08). Key findings so far: \n- Metric analysis: several isolated high-severity single-point spikes on MySQL (Mysql01/Mysql02) around ~16:30–16:43 (severity_ratio ≈ 19), but these DB spikes did NOT correspond to trace anomalies. Many MG metric flags are due to global_p95 == 0 (zero baseline) producing infinite ratios and are likely not meaningful without absolute-threshold filtering. Some MG JVM memory KPIs show small positive severity (e.g., MG01 HeapMemoryUsed ≈ +6.9%).\n- Trace analysis: pervasive short (mostly 2-minute) fault-intervals across MG01 and MG02 (MG02: 385/393 intervals in the metric detection step), and many dockerA/dockerB and Tomcat traces show transient row_count/duration spikes. The largest single relative trace deviation among Tomcat services is Tomcat03 trace.self.duration_mean (~+25% at ~16:48). MG trace intervals begin as early as ~16:30–16:32 and are frequent throughout the window.\n- Logs/error_logs: error_logs.csv is empty and prior log aggregates showed log.error_count P95 = 0 for many services; no obvious high-volume error logs were found earlier.\nReasoning to proceed: traces implicate MG01/MG02 as the layer with widespread, repeated anomalies; Tomcat03 shows the most notable relative trace increase among Tomcats. To determine the single root cause component and exact occurrence time we must use logs to confirm whether any service recorded application-level errors, GC pauses, or warnings that coincide with the earliest trace/metric fault intervals. Logs can also help identify the resource type (e.g., GC/Heap, network errors, disk errors) that caused the trace spikes. Therefore the next atomic step is a targeted log analysis of the suspect components (MG01, MG02, Tomcat01–Tomcat04, Mysql01, Mysql02, IG01, dockerA1/A2, dockerB1/B2) within the incident window to find any non-zero error_count, GC pause spikes, or other informative log KPIs and earliest timestamps. ",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Load log.csv and compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, log_name) over the full series (do NOT filter by window for thresholds). Then filter log.csv to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and restrict rows to these components: MG01, MG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, Mysql01, Mysql02, IG01, dockerA1, dockerA2, dockerB1, dockerB2. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) in that set, compute: global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count where (value >= global_p95) OR (log_name contains 'error' and value > 0), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp meeting the criteria), max_value_in_window, and severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95 (report inf if global_p95==0). Return a compact table (max 20 rows) sorted by severity_ratio desc then anomaly_point_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_point_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio. Also return a one-row-per-component summary showing component, total_anomaly_log_groups (count of log_names flagged), and earliest_log_anomaly_timestamp. Keep outputs bounded (<=20 rows for detail)."
}

{
"analysis": "We have completed threshold calculation and multi-signal anomaly detection across metrics, traces, and logs for the incident window (2021-03-09 16:30→17:00+08). Results show widespread short trace faults concentrated on MG01/MG02 starting ~16:30 and many metric flags across nodes, but many metric/log flags are due to zero-baseline P95==0 (producing infinite ratios). MySQL had isolated, very large metric spikes (severity_ratio ≈ 19) at ~16:30–16:43 but without matching trace anomalies. Tomcat nodes show small GC pause and row_count increases (Tomcat02 gc_pause_max severity ≈ 0.56). To localize a single root cause, we must focus on anomalies that are both meaningful and substantial: i.e., non-zero global P95 and severity significantly greater than the threshold (use the rule-of-thumb >50% breach). Identifying the earliest such substantial anomaly across metrics/traces/logs will give a strong candidate for the root cause component and occurrence time. The next step is therefore to extract, for each candidate component, only those anomaly events in the window that have meaningful severity (severity_ratio >= 0.5 for metrics/traces; for logs include value>global_p95 and treat log.error_count>0 as important). This will produce a concise cross-signal earliest-occurrence table we can use to select the root cause.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "Using metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv: 1) compute global P95 per series over the full available data (do NOT restrict for thresholds). 2) Filter all rows to the incident window 2021-03-09 16:30:00+08 → 2021-03-09 17:00:00+08 and restrict to components: MG01, MG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, Mysql01, Mysql02, IG01, dockerA1, dockerA2, dockerB1, dockerB2. 3) For metrics and traces, flag anomaly rows where value >= global_p95 AND global_p95 > 0, compute severity_ratio = (value - global_p95)/global_p95, and keep only rows with severity_ratio >= 0.5 (>=50%). For logs, flag rows where (value > global_p95 AND global_p95 > 0 AND severity_ratio >= 0.5) OR (log_name contains 'error' AND value > 0). 4) Produce two compact outputs:\n   A) Per-component earliest-high-severity-anomaly table (one row per component) with columns: cmdb_id, signal_type (metric/trace/log), series_name (kpi_name/trace_name/log_name), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, value_at_earliest, global_p95, severity_ratio. If a component has no such high-severity events, show nulls.\n   B) Detailed high-severity anomaly list (max 20 rows) showing: cmdb_id, signal_type, series_name, timestamp, value, global_p95, severity_ratio. \nReturn both tables. Keep outputs bounded (<=13 rows for A, <=20 rows for B)."
}

